WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified standalone formula reference for geometric image formation,
motion blur, and the fundamental physical limits of sampling.

WHY IT EXISTS
Motion blur, shutter angle, aperture, and Nyquist are the mechanical
cornerstones of camera operation. A single reference guarantees that
every GIOP motion‑compensated effect (timewarp, de‑blur, synthetic
shutter) obeys the same physical laws.

HOW IT WORKS
Formulas for blur length, shutter speed / angle conversion, and the
sampling theorem are defined.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Shutter simulation (CGI and virtual production)
- Rolling‑shutter artefact calculation
- Motion‑compensated temporal filtering

WHO USES IT
L2 VFX Engineers; compositors; camera tracking teams.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Prevents mismatches between synthetic motion blur and real camera blur
by anchoring all calculations to the same optical and mechanical models.

1. Motion Blur (Linear Subject)
   Blur_length = V * T
   V = subject velocity (pixels/s), T = exposure time (s).

2. Cinematic Motion Blur (180° Shutter)
   T = 1 / (2 * Frame_Rate)
   Blur_length = V / (2 * Frame_Rate)

3. Aperture (f‑number)
   N = f / D
   f = focal length, D = entrance pupil diameter.

4. Nyquist Sampling Theorem
   f_s > 2 * B
   f_s = sampling frequency (pixel⁻¹), B = max spatial frequency in
   the optical image. Violation causes aliasing.

5. Quantum Efficiency (QE)
   η(λ) = n_electron / n_photon
   n_electron = collected charge carriers, n_photon = incident photons.

6. Saturation‑based ISO (ISO 12232)
   S_sat = 78 / H_sat
   H_sat = exposure (lux·s) that saturates the sensor.

7. Path Tracing (Rendering Equation)
   L_o(x, ω_o) = L_e(x, ω_o) + ∫_Ω f_r L_i (ω_i·n) dω_i

8. Subsurface Scattering (BSSRDF)
   L_o(x_o, ω_o) = ∫_A ∫_Ω S(x_i,ω_i; x_o,ω_o) L_i (ω_i·n) dω_i dA

9. Effective Motion Blur with Stabilisation
   Blur_effective = |V_subject - V_compensation| * T
   V_compensation = stabilisation‑induced image shift (pixels/s).

